          "body": "52:11-12 deliberately rewrites the original Exodus. At the first Exodus Israel ate the Passover 'in haste' (Exodus 12:11), kneaded their dough on the run, and fled with their possessions. Here Isaiah says *you will not go out in haste, nor will you go as fugitives* — the departure from Babylon will be ordered, deliberate, even priestly ('you who carry the vessels of the LORD'). Yahweh is still vanguard and rear guard (52:12), recalling the pillar of cloud and fire (Exodus 13:21; 14:19), but the tempo has changed. The first Exodus was a slave's panicked escape; the second is a redeemed people's processional return. Theologically, this signals that the new redemption is more secure than the old — they leave not because they fear Pharaoh but because Yahweh has gone before them."
